John Edward: Language skills are essential to the people of the world
The independent schools of Scotland have a prehistory of academic excellence, which continued in 2018, with a number of excellent results in the exams, which were only further strengthened by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), are struggling to provide their students and parents with the best possible level of service.
The aim of the independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and highest levels of education, the professional career they will choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a school curriculum on demand, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable lesson in choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, then what you say goes into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say enters into his heart."
This is a strong reminder of the fact that we cannot just rely on English if we want to build relations and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's examinations, we find that the languages are at the top of the performance tables, with the highest success rates in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students studying foreign languages achieved degrees in graduation A.
Data gathered by 74 schools of SCIS showed that 72 percent of the pupils achieved degree degrees in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French and 63 percent of those studying Spanish also had degrees A.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages, today, as a selection course, are considered as important as courses in science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curriculum of independent schools and elsewhere.
Survey of the UK Employment and Skills Committee in 2014 revealed that, with regard to the reasons why employers had difficulty in filling job vacancies, 17 per cent of them concerned a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming increasingly urgent so that young people are prepared for their future careers.
Since more future employment opportunities require linguistic knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, because of this skill that you can use throughout your life.
If anyone is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over competition.
According to a YouGov survey in more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 per cent of respondents were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, while French was the only language to speak a two-digit percentage of respondents (15 per cent).
For this reason, investment in language teaching today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, particularly the languages of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find jobs with meaning.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered most important for the UK in 2020, such as mandarins or Japanese.
For whatever your child is interested in, there will always be some languages to choose from independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this area.
The independent schools of Scotland provide with devotion a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to achieve, no matter what the future holds them up.
One cannot deny today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for Scottish youth.
They have to.
