National Trust eavesdroppes the secret life of bats
A new survey conducted on a farm in Highlands, Scotland, seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape when chasing their food.
The findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to the planning of future environmental protection actions.
The study by Scots scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will explore the habits of the common nanny bat and small bat, as well as Dobenton's brown bat and mystery in Inverewe Gardens, in Western Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the estate to monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NTS personnel and volunteers will also carry out mobile searches using hand detectors.
The analysis of the sound of all recordings by experts will determine the frequency of bat calls, as well as which species have this behavior.
Then, a map of the habitat and a report will be created in order to form a detailed picture of their landscape-wide behaviour.
Rob Duar, a natural protection adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by every species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of biotopes management, such as the creation of meadows and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have fallen significantly since last century.
They are threatened by building and development projects affecting the parts where they mourn and destroy their habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as well as flies and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes to catch their prey.
They use an advanced audio-location technique to detect insects and obstacles in the course of their flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, considers bats to be very important.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out surveys, inspect the places where bats are tired and sometimes rescue them.
The organization has also created the first and only refuge in Scotland for bats on the Treave estate, in Dampris and Galloway, where eight out of the ten kinds of bats in Scotland live.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, states that the estate is the perfect ground for bats.
"Here in Three we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many large trees and an ideal habitat.
There is still much we do not know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what is needed to increase their populations."
It stresses the importance of first checking for bats before any house maintenance work, as the destruction of a single nest with small ones could kill up to 400 females and young ones, possibly eliminating the entire local population.
Bats are protected species and it is forbidden to kill them, harass them or disturb their peace or destroy their nests.
Elizabeth Ferrel, a member of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, encouraged the public to offer his help.
He said: "There is a lot left to learn about our bats and about many of our species, we simply do not know how their population develops."
